Is it going to be a better year for migrants?
DUBLIN – Two major lessons can be drawn from the Mediterranean migration crisis.
Firstly, Europe and the international community are applying a system cruelly ill-suited to protecting the most vulnerable migrants.
Secondly, in the face of this system's ineffectiveness, populist actors continue to exploit fears to gain political support, undermining liberal and tolerant societies that have been constructed through 70 years of relentless effort.
This is why it is essential that a genuinely proactive approach be undertaken this year at both the European and global levels.
In September next year, UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon will convene an extraordinary summit aimed at building a solid global system for protecting the most vulnerable migrants and refugees.
Let's hope that states will be ready to engage in a concrete and sustainable manner.
This necessary engagement was cruelly lacking in the course of 2015.
In fact, the international community would have been able to limit the gravity of last year's crisis if it had provided even the most modest support to the frontline countries – Turkey, Lebanon, and Jordan – which together host no less than four million refugees.
With approximately 10 billion euros, these countries would have been more capable of housing, feeding, and providing education to refugees, thereby reducing the temptation to flee to Europe.
This failure could cost Germany nothing but 21 billion € each year in the times to come.
But the financial implications of the crisis are in no way comparable to its human and political cost.
More than a million people risked their lives last year crossing the Mediterranean, enduring an exhausting journey through the Balkans.
Close to 4,000 migrants lost their lives, with many European countries turning their backs on the survivors by refusing to give them refuge.
The most cynical politicians have mercilessly exploited the fear of citizens, promoting a despicable nationalist vision either by ignoring or distorting the migrants' life experience.
In the United States, for example, not a single one of the 780,000 refugees installed since September 11, 2001, has been found guilty of terrorist activity.
At the same time, immigrants generally pay more taxes than they benefit from social benefits.
And yet, extremist parties are flirting dangerously with the seizure of political power in certain European countries, and are currently gaining support even within the former bastions of liberalism.
Anti-immigration parties are already in power in Hungary and Poland.
Their success is meanwhile prompting traditional parties to promote their own policy hostile to immigration.
This situation has significantly disrupted European cooperation.
The EU program aimed at dealing with the million refugees arrived on its shores has only allowed 190 to be "relocated".
The border controls of six Schengen space member states have been reinstated, at least provisionally.
In the eyes of the rest of the world, the EU appears today as nationalist and incompetent.
Of course, the resolution of this crisis does not only concern Europe; responsibility cannot be defined by simple geographical proximity.
The EU is undoubtedly facing a threat to its own existence today, which it will only be able to overcome by firmly demonstrating the international solidarity and leadership it is capable of.
Therefore, it is up to the member states to take the initiative by proposing solutions.
The most urgent priority is to establish legal and secure channels for refugees to reach Europe.
This is not to say that each migrant in difficulty must be welcomed.
However, it is incumbent upon the EU to be more systematically generous in determining the number of refugees to be welcomed, and to employ orderly mechanisms to facilitate their entry.
A system of this kind would allow for the protection of migrants while saving Europe (thanks to the possibility of fully examining the requests).
Going beyond an approach aimed at discouraging asylum seekers from risking their lives by crossing the Mediterranean, this approach would allow for the projection of an image of solidarity towards countries on the front line, which continue to host the majority of refugees.
An aspect just as important, this approach would encourage the rest of the international community to contribute to the efforts.
This leads us to the second priority of 2016: building a solid global system for the protection of vulnerable refugees and migrants.
This goal will require, above all, that more countries agree to accept refugees.
Over the past few years, the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees has only been able to resettle fewer than 75,000 out of the approximately 20 million annual refugees.
Several million of them end up in a prolonged migration situation, with an estimated average duration of 25 years, prisoners of a kind of purgatory and uncertain about the day of a possible return to their country.
In 2016, it is necessary that developed countries agree to admit a cumulative number close to one million refugees each year, either through their resettlement or by granting them humanitarian, student, professional, or other visas.
Canada having stated that it would accept 50,000 Syrian refugees this year alone, it is a clearly achievable goal.
At the same time, the international community will have to support the integration of refugees in major host countries such as Turkey, Kenya, Lebanon, and Jordan.
At the current state of affairs, these countries receive only a fraction of the $3,000 to $5,000 annually necessary for each refugee for housing, food, care, education, and vocational training in the first years of installation.
And these numbers do not take into account the necessary cost of constructing or upgrading infrastructure.
For example, in Lebanon, water supply systems are suffering from the massive influx of refugees' pressure.
In exchange for funding, host countries could commit to fully integrating refugees into their schools, labor market, and civic institutions.
However, effective migrant integration will only be possible if European countries and others get rid of their prejudices concerning migrants.
If these individuals continue to be seen as a burden, or even a threat to security, the reactionary political forces will cease to gain ground, depriving new arrivals of opportunities and transforming fear into a self-fulfilling prophecy.
On the other hand, if the host states manage to integrate migrants with enthusiasm, each party will benefit – including these countries (notably via income entries).
Last month, in Paris, the international community proved that it was capable of subordinating its national interests to a broader global objective: the fight against climate change.
It is necessary in 2016 that a similar effort aims to build a better protection system for migrants.
This is a question of life or death for some 20 million refugees, for several million other vulnerable migrants – as well as a profound test of the civic health of democratic societies around the world.
